properties.Title: Weather Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Winter Weather Travel Advisory in effect from late this afternoon through Sunday morning. Lake effect flurries have developed late this afternoon off Lake Huron and Georgian Bay. The activity should intensify this evening with a threat of snow squalls. Some areas may see snowfall amounts of 10 cm by Sunday morning. In addition, northwest winds gusting up to 50 km/h may result in areas of blowing snow giving reduced visibility. The lake effect activity is expected to diminish Sunday morning. Motorists are urged to exercise caution. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Accumulating snow expected on Sunday. Total snowfall: 5 to 15 cm, possibly higher over parts of the eastern mainland and Cape Breton Time span: Before dawn Sunday morning into Sunday night. Location: all of Nova Scotia Remarks: A disturbance will approach the Maritimes later tonight and spread snow to much of the province Sunday. In the west and along parts of the Atlantic coast, the precipitation will start as rain and then change to snow early Sunday morning. At this time, the highest amounts are expected over eastern sections of the province where the snow will persist into the evening. General snowfall amounts of 5 to 15 cm are expected, with locally higher amounts possible over eastern regions. However, should the intensity or track of this system shift from what is currently expected, these amounts could change. Additionally, strong northerly winds will develop later on Sunday, especially over the eastern half of the province, and combine with the fresh snow to create reduced visibility in blowing snow. The combination of snow and blowing snow could impact travel in parts of the province later on Sunday. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Heavy snowfall with blowing snow is expected. Total snowfall: 20 to 40 cm. Maximum wind gusts: Northeast 60 to 80 km/h beginning Sunday evening increasing to northerly 100 km/h overnight. Locations: southeastern Newfoundland. Time span: Sunday afternoon through Monday morning. Remarks: 2 to 5 cm of snow can be expected across southeastern Newfoundland Sunday afternoon. The snow will then become heavy in the evening and persist overnight. Accumulations of 20 to 40 cm are forecast by dawn on Monday, with the highest amounts over the northeastern Avalon. Slightly lesser accumulations are expected along the southern shore and parts of the southern Avalon as the snow is expected to mix with ice pellets Sunday evening. Snow and blowing snow will result in reduced visibility which may impact Monday morning commuters. Whiteout conditions are expected over exposed areas overnight and into Monday morning. Conditions are expected to begin improve near noon on Monday. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
